Date: Wed, 26 May 1999 09:51:11 -0600 (Mountain Daylight Time)
From: Jeff Root <jroot@cvmbs.colostate.edu>

Some confusion still exists pertaining to the taxonomy of "elk" in North
America in a 99 issue of ProMED-mail. First, I believe that the North
American elk species in question is what is commonly referred to as Rocky
Mountain elk or wapiti. The current scientific name for this species is
_Cervus elaphus_. This has been the case for some time now. Roosevelt elk
(_C. elaphus roosevelti_) are common in the Pacific Northwest region of the
United States and remnant populations of tule elk (_C. elaphus
nannodes_)still exist in California. It appears that some confusion about
the latter still exists. In literature from the 1990's, this subspecies was
termed as _C. elaphus nannodes_, _C. nannodes_, and _C. canadensis.
However, _C. elaphus nannodes_ is by far the most commonly used Latin name
in the literature at this time.
I agree that there is an imperative need to use the Latin name of an animal
when discussing it. However, using the proper literature to get this
information is also imperative. Field guides are typically highly
discouraged if not barred for use as citations in ecological-type journals.
The use of more recent literature from well-accepted sources would help to
alleviate this problem.
Some examples include:
Wilson, D. E., and D. M. Reeder (eds). 1993. Mammal Species of the World.
Smithsonian Institution Press, 1206 pp. (Available from Smithsonian
Institution Press, 1-800-782-4612 or
703-435-7809.)
Hall, E. R. 1981. The mammals of North America. Wiley, New York, NY. ?
pp. (An excellent reference, but this volume is nearly two decades old
now). [Furthermore, it is likely out of print and getting quite old itself.
Fitzgerald, J.P., C.A. Meaney, and D.M. Armstrong. 1994. Mammals of
Colorado. Denver Museum of Natural History and Univ. Press of Colorado,
Niwot, CO. 467 pp.

There are many other excellent state taxonomy books not listed here.
--
J.Jeffrey Root
e-mail: jroot@cvmbs.colostate.edu
