[2
Date: Wed, 26 May 1999 16:27:50 -0600
From: Jerry Haigh <jerry.haigh@usask.ca>

The use of the taxonomic name _Cervus canadensis_ to describe the
NorthAmerican Elk in a recent posting is not current.The animal is actually
a member of the genus _Cervus _, but considered a member of the species
_elaphus_. _C. elaphus_ consists of red deer and wapiti (N. American elk),
which are both members of the sub-family Cervinae. If writers stick to the
word wapiti (derived from a Shawnee word in reference to the white rump),
there will be no confusion with the term elk, (which is variously rendered
in Europe as elch, alg, and no doubt others), and of course refers to
_Alces alces_ (the moose, in English), and its subspecies.
The type species of _Cervus elaphus_ is the red deer. In North America
there are four extant subspecies of this animal. These are _C.e.nelsoni_,
_C.e. nannodes_, _C.e. manitobensis_, and _C.e. roosevelti_.
It is of course possible that DNA work currently in progress will
distinguish between red deer and wapiti and that they may end up as
separate species. However, for now, the species should be called _Cervus
elaphus_. By and large they consist of a kline that starts at its smallest
in Scotland, and gets bigger as one goes eastwards. The splitters have them
in many sub-species. There is no doubt at all that an animal as large as
the North American races exists in Mongolia
By using _Cervus canadensis_ there is a real chance for confusion as there
are two extinct subspecies of wapiti. One is _C.e.canadensis_, the other
_C.e.merriami_.
For more details consult Farming Wapiti and Red Deer, 1993. Haigh JC and
Hudson RJ. Mosby Year Book.
On an epidemiological note, the spread of brucellosis among wapiti in the
USA has occurred when animals eat fodder contaminated with periparturient
fluids containing _Brucella abortus_. The high concentrations of the
animals on feeding grounds, and the abortions that do occur in infected
animals are at the root of the problem. In animals that live elsewhere,
where winter feeding is not occurring, do not seem to sustain brucellosis
in the wild. This may be due to the fact that normal calving behaviour of
wapiti consists of a period from some 24- 48 hours before delivery when the
female seeks solitude. She may not return to the herd for a couple of
weeks. She will certainly lick her calf, even as it is being born, graze
any grass where birthing fluids are passed and then clean off and eat the
fetal membranes followed by the placenta proper. For a reference consult
Thorne, E.T, Brucellsois. In: Diseases of Wildlife in Wyoming. 1982.
eds. Thorne, Kingston, Jolley & Bergstrom. publ. Wyoming Game & Fish Dept.
A note on placenta eating. Although most people consider that this is an
anti-predator behaviour, there are almost certainly another, and perhaps
more fundamental reasons for this behaviour in almost all terrestrial
eutherian mammals (S. American camelids are an exception)
--
Jerry Haigh
e-mail: jerry.haigh@usask.ca
